{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"tokens":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"struct"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"DeadLetter"}],"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["macOS"]}]},{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"overview","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Often the reason for this is that the message was sent to given actor while it was still alive,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"yet once it arrived the destination node the actor had already terminated, leaving the message to be dropped."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Since such races can happen when a distributed remote actor is e.g. passivated before it receives a remote call,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and can be tricky to diagnose otherwise, such messages are  such messages are not silently dropped,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"but rather logged, with as much information as available (e.g. about the sender or source location of the initiating tell),"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"such that when operating the system, bugs regarding undelivered messages can be spotted and fixed."}]},{"anchor":"Not-all-dead-letters-are-problems","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Not all dead letters are problems"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"No, some dead letters may happen in a perfectly healthy system and if one knows that a message could arrive"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"“too late” or be dropped for some other reason, one may mark it using the TODO: “dont log me as dead letter” protocol."}]},{"anchor":"Trivia","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Trivia"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The term dead letters, or rather “dead letter office” originates from the postal system, where undeliverable"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"mail would be called such, and shipped to one specific place to deal with these letters."}]}]}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"sections":[],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/distributedcluster\/deadletter"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"relationshipsSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/DistributedCluster\/Se","doc:\/\/DistributedCluster\/SE"],"kind":"relationships","title":"Conforms To","type":"conformsTo"}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/DistributedCluster\/documentation\/DistributedCluster\/DeadLetter","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A “dead letter” is a message (“letter”) that is impossible to deliver to its designated recipient."}],"kind":"symbol","metadata":{"fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"struct"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"DeadLetter"}],"title":"DeadLetter","roleHeading":"Structure","role":"symbol","symbolKind":"struct","externalID":"s:18DistributedCluster10DeadLetterV","modules":[{"name":"DistributedCluster"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"DeadLetter"}]},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/DistributedCluster\/documentation\/DistributedCluster"]]},"topicSections":[{"title":"Initializers","identifiers":["doc:\/\/DistributedCluster\/documentation\/DistributedCluster\/DeadLetter\/init(_:recipient:sentAtFile:sentAtLine:)"]}],"references":{"doc://DistributedCluster/documentation/DistributedCluster":{"role":"collection","title":"DistributedCluster","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A peer-to-peer cluster actor system implementation for Swift."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/DistributedCluster\/documentation\/DistributedCluster","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/distributedcluster"},"doc://DistributedCluster/documentation/DistributedCluster/DeadLetter/init(_:recipient:sentAtFile:sentAtLine:)":{"role":"symbol","title":"init(_:recipient:sentAtFile:sentAtLine:)","fragments":[{"kind":"identifier